      summary: "African Indigenous Churches arose in the late 19th and early 20th centuries as African Christians responded to racial discrimination in mission churches, cultural imperialism, and the inadequacy of Western Christianity to address African spiritual needs. Two main types emerged: Ethiopian-type separatist churches (breaking away over governance) and Aladura/Spirit-type churches (emphasizing healing, prophecy, and direct Spirit encounter in African forms). The AICs represent a massive assertion of African Christian identity and creativity, and today number in the hundreds of millions worldwide.",
